**8.2 Regional Variations**

Pension systems vary significantly by region. Western states tend to
have larger statewide systems with consolidated administration.
Northeastern states often have multiple separate systems and higher
benefit levels. Southern states generally have lower benefits but better
funded systems. Midwestern states show wide variation in both benefits
and funding.

**8.3 Local Systems**

While statewide systems receive the most attention, thousands of local
pension systems serve municipal employees. Colorado provides an example
of local pension complexity with 61 separate locally-administered
pension plans in addition to the statewide PERA system. These local
plans vary widely in size, benefit structure, and administrative
sophistication, facing unique challenges including limited staff
resources, difficulty attracting actuarial expertise, and governance
structures that may lack appropriate checks and balances.

**9. Market Trends and Evolution**

**9.1 Benefit Design Evolution**

Many states have implemented tier systems providing different benefits
based on hire date. Newer employees typically receive lower benefits
than predecessors, with changes including reduced accrual rates, longer
final average salary periods, later retirement ages, and lower
cost-of-living adjustments. The Denver Employees Retirement Plan
exemplifies this with three tiers based on hire date.

Several states have adopted hybrid plans combining defined benefit and
defined contribution elements, including Virginia\'s optional hybrid
plan, Tennessee\'s mandatory hybrid for new hires since 2014, and
Utah\'s hybrid design. Some systems have implemented risk-sharing
mechanisms that adjust benefits or contributions based on plan
experience.

**9.2 Contribution Trends**

Employer contribution rates have increased dramatically from an average
of 9.41% of payroll in 2001 to 31.65% in 2024. Some distressed systems
require contributions exceeding 40% of payroll. Rising pension costs
have crowded out other public spending, with pension contributions
increasingly competing with education, infrastructure, and services.

**9.3 Investment Strategy Evolution**

Public pension investment strategies have evolved with shift from bonds
to equities during the 1980s and 1990s, increased allocation to
alternative investments including private equity, real estate, and hedge
funds, growing emphasis on environmental, social, and governance
factors, and ongoing debate over active versus passive management.

**10. Technology and Administration Market**

**10.1 Market Size and Growth**

The pension administration software market reached \$4.93 billion in
2025 and is projected to grow to \$7.43 billion by 2030, representing an
8.60% compound annual growth rate. This growth is driven by urgent need
to replace aging legacy systems, regulatory pressure for real-time
reporting and transparency, rising member expectations for digital
self-service, and government modernization mandates with dedicated
funding.

**10.2 Deployment Trends**

Cloud-based deployments have become dominant, representing 60.40% of the
market in 2024 and growing at a 12.80% CAGR. The shift to cloud is
driven by reduced capital expenditure requirements, easier system
updates and maintenance, improved disaster recovery capabilities, and
better scalability. However, on-premises deployments persist in
jurisdictions with data localization requirements.

**10.3 Legacy System Challenges**

A striking feature of the public pension technology landscape is the
prevalence of legacy systems. Government at all levels remains dependent
on legacy systems, which consume 70-80% of IT budgets for maintenance
rather than innovation. Many pension systems continue to operate on
platforms developed in the 1970s and 1980s with COBOL-based mainframe
applications, critical business logic embedded in undocumented code,
difficult and expensive integration with modern systems, staff with
legacy expertise retiring, and incomplete or nonexistent documentation.

**10.4 Modernization Approaches**

Pension systems considering modernization face several strategic
choices: complete system replacement with modern commercial software,
rehosting to modern infrastructure without code changes, refactoring by
rewriting using modern languages and architectures, encapsulating legacy
systems with modern interfaces, and integrating legacy systems to modern
front-ends and analytics. Large-scale pension system replacements are
notoriously risky, with numerous high-profile failures including the
California PERS 21st Century project abandoned in 2012 after spending
over \$250 million.

**10.5 Self-Service Portal Growth**

Member self-service portals are expanding rapidly, growing at a 12.50%
CAGR. Modern portals allow members to view account balances and
projected benefits, run benefit estimates with different retirement
scenarios, update personal information and beneficiary designations,
submit retirement applications online, and access tax documents and
payment history.

**11. Key Industry Organizations**

**11.1 Professional Associations**

Several professional organizations serve the public pension community.
The National Association of State Retirement Administrators (NASRA) is
the primary association for state and local government pension
administrators, providing research, education, and advocacy. The
National Council on Teacher Retirement (NCTR) represents public pension
systems serving teachers and education employees. The Government Finance
Officers Association (GFOA) provides best practices guidance for
government finance including pension administration and accounting. The
Conference of Consulting Actuaries (CCA) represents actuaries providing
consulting services to public pension plans.

**11.2 Research Organizations**

Key research organizations include the Equable Institute providing
detailed funding analysis for 253 major public pension systems, the
Center for Retirement Research at Boston College conducting academic
research on retirement security, the Reason Foundation performing policy
analysis with focus on pension reform, RAND Corporation researching
pension funding and reform strategies, and the Urban Institute analyzing
pension policy and state/local fiscal issues.

**11.3 Standard-Setting Bodies**

Standard-setting bodies include the Governmental Accounting Standards
Board (GASB) setting accounting and reporting standards for state and
local governments including pensions, the Actuarial Standards Board
(ASB) issuing Actuarial Standards of Practice governing pension
actuarial work, and the American Academy of Actuaries (AAA) as the
professional organization setting qualification standards for actuaries.

**12. Implications for NoUI**

**12.1 Market Opportunity**

The public pension landscape presents significant opportunities for
NoUI\'s approach to modernization. Vast legacy infrastructure creates
urgent need for modernization. Failed replacement projects have made
systems wary of big-bang approaches. The middleware approach addresses
risk concerns while enabling progressive improvement. Split architecture
with cloud AI and on-premises data addresses security and compliance
requirements. Local plans like Colorado\'s 61 locally-administered
systems are underserved by enterprise vendors.

**12.2 Competitive Landscape**

NoUI\'s approach differs from traditional vendors. Enterprise vendors
like Sagitec, Vitech, and CPAS focus on complete system replacement.
Consulting firms often recommend multi-year transformation projects.
NoUI\'s middleware approach enables value without replacing existing
systems. AI-driven workspace composition is unique in the market.

**12.3 Key Success Factors**

Based on this industry analysis, NoUI should emphasize calculation
accuracy as pension systems require absolute precision, transparency by
showing all work since systems have been burned by black-box solutions,
auditability ensuring every calculation is traceable to governing
documents, incremental deployment enabling value without full system
replacement, legacy integration working with existing databases rather
than requiring migration, and compliance awareness understanding GASB,
IRS, and state-specific requirements.

**12.4 Denver POC Strategic Value**

The Denver Employees Retirement Plan POC provides an ideal demonstration
platform. Its three-tier structure demonstrates handling of benefit
complexity. Local administration reflects target market characteristics.
Colorado\'s 61 local plans provide immediate expansion opportunity.
Moderate size enables comprehensive demonstration without overwhelming
scope. DERP\'s challenges including multiple tiers, DROs, and purchased
service are representative of industry complexity.

**12.5 Long-Term Vision**

NoUI\'s market position should emphasize progressive modernization
without operational disruption. The platform should be positioned as the
safest path to modernization for risk-averse pension systems, a solution
preserving institutional knowledge while enabling new capabilities, an
approach delivering value in months not years, and a platform growing
more intelligent through cross-system learning while maintaining strict
data isolation.

